{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496882"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:58:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:58:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1427"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1427"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.66,0.18,0.02,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1427"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105682"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1427"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1427"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88134"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"284"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2765"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"7861"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1666"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1701"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9878"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9912"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33835"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38065"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42315"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105682"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 69-year-old man presents to the hospital with dull chest pain that has persisted over the past 45 mins. On examination he has a marked bradycardia of 44 beats/min and has a blood pressure of 84/62 mmHg. An ECG is recorded (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of these medications are most appropriate as a part of initial therapy for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IV nitrates","Antiplatelet therapy","Morphine","Beta blocker","ACE inhibitor"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAcute coronary syndromes (ACS) are most commonly caused by a rupture in atherosclerotic plaques and subsequent thrombosis that occludes the coronary vessel. The immediate intervention is revascularisation with percutaneous intervention or fibrinolysis. All patients who present with a STEMI should be pre-treated with\u003Cstrong\u003E dual antiplatelet therapy (DAPT)\u003C/strong\u003E before reperfusion. Initial choice of DAPT in STEMI depends on the revascularisation approach: for primary PCI, aspirin and a potent P2Y\u003Csub\u003E12\u003C/sub\u003E receptor inhibitor (ticagrelor or prasugrel) are favoured; for fibrinolysis, aspirin and clopidogrel are favoured. If patients require oral anticoagulation or cannot receive a potent P2Y\u003Csub\u003E12\u003C/sub\u003E receptor inhibitor, then clopidogrel should be prescribed. For patients with non-ST elevation ACS (NSTEACS), either aspirin and clopidogrel or aspirin and ticagrelor can be prescribed, although considering de-prescribing from ticagrelor to aspirin after 30 days due to higher bleeding risk. Note prasugrel is not available in Australia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuration of DAPT depends on the risk of ischaemia balanced against risk of bleeding \u2013 generally, patients will be on DAPT between 1-12 months depending on this risk/benefit analysis. The Australian 2025 ACS Guidelines have recently recommended longer term therapy with P2Y\u003Csub\u003E12\u003C/sub\u003E receptor inhibitor (clopidogrel or ticagrelor) rather than aspirin for single antiplatelet therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV nitrates\u003C/strong\u003E can be used in the acute setting to treat chest pain that persists after the use of sublingual tablets. However, this patient has a marked bradycardia of 45 beats per minute and the use of nitrates is contraindicated due to the risk of haemodynamic decompensation. This may be due to the widespread vasodilator properties of nitrates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough recent evidence has begun to question the use of \u003Cstrong\u003Emorphine \u003C/strong\u003Ein ACS due to some research findings indicating an increased risk of in-hospital mortality, the 2016 Australian and the 2023 European Guidelines maintain that morphine may still be considered as analgesia for patients with ongoing chest pain despite other anti-ischaemic therapies. However, morphine may enhance nausea and vomiting and slow the gastrointestinal absorption of oral medicines, which may delay the onset of action of orally administered antiplatelet therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta-blockers\u003C/strong\u003E should be administered early to those with an acute STEMI who have no contraindications. It reduces ischaemia by decreasing myocardial oxygen demand. However, the marked bradycardia and hypotension indicates that the patient is hemodynamically compromised, and the use of beta-blocker could further exacerbate the situation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EACE inhibitors \u003C/strong\u003Ehave been shown to improve mortality following an acute MI due to their ability to limit infarct size and reduce ventricular remodelling. However, they are used as a strategy for secondary prevention and are typically prescribed as part of late and post-hospital pharmacotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["All patients who present with a STEMI should be treated with dual antiplatelet therapy (DAPT)"],"references":["Chew DP, Scott IA, Cullen L, French JK, Briffa TG, Tideman PA, Woodruffe S, Kerr A, Branagan M, Aylward PE. National Heart Foundation of Australia and Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand: Australian clinical guidelines for the management of acute coronary syndromes 2016. Medical Journal of Australia. 2016 Aug;205(3):128-33. https://www.heartfoundation.org.au/getmedia/6132a46d-5cfc-4cec-a9da-2ff380179bb1/Clinical_Guidelines_for_the_Management_of_Acute_Coronary_Syndromes_2016.pdf","Byrne RA, Rossello X, Coughlan JJ, Barbato E, Berry C, Chieffo A, Claeys MJ, Dan GA, Dweck MR, Galbraith M, Gilard M. 2023 ESC Guidelines for the management of acute coronary syndromes: Developed by the task force on the management of acute coronary syndromes of the European Society of Cardiology (ESC). European Heart Journal. 2023 Aug 25:ehad191. https://academic.oup.com/eurheartj/advance-article/doi/10.1093/eurheartj/ehad191/7243210","Kandan S, Johnson T. Contemporary Antiplatelet Strategies in the Treatment of STEMI using Primary Percutaneous Coronary Intervention. Interventional Cardiology Review. 2015;10(1):26.","Komosa A, Lesiak M, Siniawski A, Mularek-Kubzdela T, Grajek S. Expert reviews Significance of antiplatelet therapy in emergency myocardial infarction treatment. Advances in Interventional Cardiology. 2014;1:32-39.","National Heart Foundation of Australia \u0026 Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand. \u201cACS Guideline 2025.\u201d Heart Foundation, 2025, www.heartfoundation.org.au/for-professionals/acs-guideline?tab=0."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88134"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1427"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"2176"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"2176","links":{"self":"